[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The **assignment problem** is a fundamental combinatorial optimization problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] that may vary depending on the agent-task assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] of maximum size, in which the sum of weights of the edges is minimum.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If the numbers of agents and tasks are equal, then the problem is called **balanced assignment**, and the graph-theoretic version is called **minimum-cost perfect matching**.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Otherwise, it is called **unbalanced assignment**.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If the total cost of the assignment for all tasks is equal to the sum of the costs for each agent (or the sum of the costs for each task, which is the same thing in this case), then the problem is called **linear assignment**.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Commonly, when speaking of the *assignment problem* without any additional qualification, then the *linear balanced assignment problem* is meant.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Suppose that a taxi firm has three taxis (the agents) available, and three customers (the tasks) wishing to be picked up as soon as possible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The firm prides itself on speedy pickups, so for each taxi the "cost" of picking up a particular customer will depend on the time taken for the taxi to reach the pickup point.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This is a *balanced assignment* problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Its solution is whichever combination of taxis and customers results in the least total cost.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Now, suppose that there are *four* taxis available, but still only three customers.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This is an *unbalanced assignment* problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] One way to solve it is to invent a fourth dummy task, perhaps called "sitting still doing nothing", with a cost of 0 for the taxi assigned to it.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This reduces the problem to a balanced assignment problem, which can then be solved in the usual way and still give the best solution to the problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Similar adjustments can be done in order to allow more tasks than agents, tasks to which multiple agents must be assigned (for instance, a group of more customers than will fit in one taxi), or maximizing profit rather than minimizing cost.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The problem is "linear" because the cost function to be optimized as well as all the constraints contain only linear terms.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] A naive solution for the assignment problem is to check all the assignments and calculate the cost of each one.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This may be very inefficient since, with *n* agents and *n* tasks, there are *n*!
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] (factorial of *n*) different assignments.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Another naive solution is to greedily assign the pair with the smallest cost first, and remove the vertices; then, among the remaining vertices, assign the pair with the smallest cost; and so on.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This algorithm may yield a non-optimal solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The greedy algorithm would assign Task 1 to Alice and Task 2 to George, for a total cost of 9, but the reverse assignment has a total cost of 7.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Fortunately, there are many algorithms for finding the optimal assignment in time polynomial in *n*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The assignment problem is a special case of the transportation problem, which is a special case of the minimum cost flow problem, which in turn is a special case of a linear program.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] While it is possible to solve any of these problems using the simplex algorithm, or in worst-case polynomial time using the ellipsoid method, each specialization has a smaller solution space and thus more efficient algorithms designed to take advantage of its special structure.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In the balanced assignment problem, both parts of the bipartite graph have the same number of vertices, denoted by *n*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] One of the first polynomial-time algorithms for balanced assignment was the Hungarian algorithm.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] It is a *global* algorithm – it is based on improving a matching along augmenting paths (alternating paths between unmatched vertices).
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Its run-time complexity, when using Fibonacci heaps, is $O(mn+n^{2}\log n)$ , where *m* is the number of edges.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This is currently the fastest run-time of a strongly polynomial algorithm for this problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Some variants of the Hungarian algorithm also benefit from parallel computing, including GPU acceleration.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If all weights are integers, then the run-time can be improved to $O(mn+n^{2}\log \log n)$ , but the resulting algorithm is only weakly polynomial.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, and all weights are at most *C* (where *C*>1 is some integer), then the problem can be solved in $O(m{\sqrt {n}}\log(n\cdot C))$ weakly-polynomial time in a method called *weight scaling*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In addition to the global methods, there are *local methods* which are based on finding local updates (rather than full augmenting paths).
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] These methods have worse asymptotic runtime guarantees, but they often work better in practice.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] These algorithms are called auction algorithms, push-relabel algorithms, or preflow-push algorithms.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Some of these algorithms were shown to be equivalent.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Some of the local methods assume that the graph admits a *perfect matching*; if this is not the case, then some of these methods might run forever.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] A simple technical way to solve this problem is to extend the input graph to a *complete bipartite graph,* by adding artificial edges with very large weights.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] These weights should exceed the weights of all existing matchings, to prevent appearance of artificial edges in the possible solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] As shown by Mulmuley, Vazirani and Vazirani, the problem of minimum weight perfect matching is converted to finding minors in the adjacency matrix of a graph.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Using the isolation lemma, a minimum weight perfect matching in a graph can be found with probability at least 1⁄2.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] For a graph with *n* vertices, it requires $O(\log ^{2}(n))$ time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In the unbalanced assignment problem, the larger part of the bipartite graph has *n* vertices and the smaller part has *r*<*n* vertices.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] There is also a constant *s* which is at most the cardinality of a maximum matching in the graph.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a minimum-cost matching of size exactly *s*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The most common case is the case in which the graph admits a one-sided-perfect matching (i.e., a matching of size *r*), and *s*=*r*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Unbalanced assignment can be reduced to a balanced assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The naive reduction is to add $n-r$ new vertices to the smaller part and connect them to the larger part using edges of cost 0.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] However, this requires $n(n-r)$ new edges.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] A more efficient reduction is called the *doubling technique*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Here, a new graph *G'* is built from two copies of the original graph *G*: a forward copy *Gf* and a backward copy *Gb.* The backward copy is "flipped", so that, in each side of *G'*, there are now *n*+*r* vertices.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] All in all, at most $n+r$ new edges are required.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The resulting graph always has a perfect matching of size $n+r$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] A minimum-cost perfect matching in this graph must consist of minimum-cost maximum-cardinality matchings in *Gf* and *Gb.* The main problem with this doubling technique is that there is no speed gain when $r\ll n$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Instead of using reduction, the unbalanced assignment problem can be solved by directly generalizing existing algorithms for balanced assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The Hungarian algorithm can be generalized to solve the problem in $O(ms+s^{2}\log r)$ strongly-polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In particular, if *s*=*r* then the runtime is $O(mr+r^{2}\log r)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, then Thorup's method can be used to get a runtime of $O(ms+s^{2}\log \log r)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The assignment problem can be solved by presenting it as a linear program.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] For convenience we will present the maximization problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Each edge (*i*,*j*), where *i* is in A and *j* is in T, has a weight ${\textstyle w_{ij}}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] For each edge ⁠ $(i,j)$ ⁠ we have a variable ${\textstyle x_{ij}}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The total weight of the matching is: $\sum _{(i,j)\in A\times T}w_{ij}x_{ij}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a maximum-weight perfect matching.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] However, we can solve it without the integrality constraints (i.e., drop the last constraint), using standard methods for solving continuous linear programs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] While this formulation allows also fractional variable values, in this special case, the LP always has an optimal solution where the variables take integer values.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This is because the constraint matrix of the fractional LP is totally unimodular – it satisfies the four conditions of Hoffman and Gale.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Other approaches for the assignment problem exist and are reviewed by Duan and Pettie (see Table II).
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Their work proposes an approximation algorithm for the assignment problem (and the more general maximum-weight matching problem), which runs in linear time for any fixed error bound.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In the basic assignment problem, each agent is assigned to at most one task and each task is assigned to at most one agent.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] In the **many-to-many assignment problem**, each agent *i* may take up to *ci* tasks (*ci* is called the agent's *capacity*), and each task *j* may be taken by up to *dj* agents simultaneously (*dj* is called the task's *capacity*).
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] If the sums of capacities in both sides are equal ( $\sum _{i}c_{i}=\sum _{j}d_{j}$ ), then the problem is *balanced*, and the goal is to find a perfect matching (assign exactly *ci* tasks to each agent *i* and exactly *dj* agents to each task *j*) such that the total cost is as small as possible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The problem can be solved by reduction to the minimum cost network flow problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] An integral maximum flow of minimum cost can be found in polynomial time; see network flow problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Every integral maximum flow in this network corresponds to a matching in which at most *ci* tasks are assigned to each agent *i* and at most *dj* agents are assigned to each task *j* (in the balanced case, exactly *ci* tasks are assigned to *i* and exactly *dj* agents are assigned to *j*).
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] A min-cost maximum flow corresponds to a min-cost assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] When phrased as a graph theory problem, the assignment problem can be extended from bipartite graphs to arbitrary graphs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] The corresponding problem, of finding a matching in a weighted graph where the sum of weights is maximized, is called the maximum-weight matching problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] Another generalization of the assignment problem is extending the number of sets to be matched from two to many.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] So that rather than matching agents to tasks, the problem is extended to matching agents to tasks to time intervals to locations.
[src:hungarian-assignment/assignment-problem] This results in Multidimensional assignment problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization is related to operations research, algorithm theory, and computational complexity theory.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] It has important applications in several fields, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, auction theory, software engineering, VLSI, applied mathematics and theoretical computer science.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] There is a large amount of literature on polynomial-time algorithms for certain special classes of discrete optimization.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] A considerable amount of it is unified by the theory of linear programming.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Some examples of combinatorial optimization problems that are covered by this framework are shortest paths and shortest-path trees, flows and circulations, spanning trees, matching, and matroid problems.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization problems can be viewed as searching for the best element of some set of discrete items; therefore, in principle, any sort of search algorithm or metaheuristic can be used to solve them.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] However, generic search algorithms are not guaranteed to find an optimal solution first, nor are they guaranteed to run quickly (in polynomial time).
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Since some discrete optimization problems are NP-complete, such as the traveling salesman (decision) problem, this is expected unless P=NP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] For each combinatorial optimization problem, there is a corresponding decision problem that asks whether there is a feasible solution for some particular measure $m_{0}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] For example, if there is a graph G which contains vertices u and v , an optimization problem might be "find a path from u to v that uses the fewest edges".
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] This problem might have an answer of, say, 4.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] A corresponding decision problem would be "is there a path from u to v that uses 10 or fewer edges?" This problem can be answered with a simple 'yes' or 'no'.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] The field of approximation algorithms deals with algorithms to find near-optimal solutions to hard problems.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] The usual decision version is then an inadequate definition of the problem since it only specifies acceptable solutions.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Even though we could introduce suitable decision problems, the problem is then more naturally characterized as an optimization problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] An *NP-optimization problem* (NPO) is a combinatorial optimization problem with the following additional conditions.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Note that the below referred polynomials are functions of the size of the respective functions' inputs, not the size of some implicit set of input instances.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] This implies that the corresponding decision problem is in NP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] In computer science, interesting optimization problems usually have the above properties and are therefore NPO problems.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] A problem is additionally called a P-optimization (PO) problem, if there exists an algorithm which finds optimal solutions in polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Often, when dealing with the class NPO, one is interested in optimization problems for which the decision versions are NP-complete.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Note that hardness relations are always with respect to some reduction.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] Due to the connection between approximation algorithms and computational optimization problems, reductions which preserve approximation in some respect are for this subject preferred than the usual Turing and Karp reductions.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] An example of such a reduction would be L-reduction.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] For this reason, optimization problems with NP-complete decision versions are not necessarily called NPO-complete.
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] An NPO problem is called *polynomially bounded* (PB) if, for every instance x and for every solution $y\in f(x)$ , the measure $m(x,y)$ is bounded by a polynomial function of the size of x .
[src:hungarian-assignment/combinatorial-optimization] The class NPOPB is the class of NPO problems that are polynomially-bounded.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The **weak duality theorem** states that the objective value of the dual LP at any feasible solution is always a bound on the objective of the primal LP at any feasible solution (upper or lower bound, depending on whether it is a maximization or minimization problem).
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In fact, this bounding property holds for the optimal values of the dual and primal LPs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The **strong duality theorem** states that, moreover, if the primal has an optimal solution then the dual has an optimal solution too, *and the two optima are equal*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] These theorems belong to a larger class of duality theorems in optimization.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The strong duality theorem is one of the cases in which the duality gap (the gap between the optimum of the primal and the optimum of the dual) is 0.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] We would like to construct an upper bound on the solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] So we create a linear combination of the constraints, with positive coefficients, such that the coefficients of **x** in the constraints are at least **c**T.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] This linear combination gives us an upper bound on the objective.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The variables **y** of the dual LP are the coefficients of this linear combination.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The dual LP tries to find such coefficients that *minimize* the resulting upper bound.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] This LP is called the *dual of* the original LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The duality theorem has an economic interpretation.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] If we interpret the primal LP as a classical "resource allocation" problem, its dual LP can be interpreted as a "resource valuation" problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Consider a factory that is planning its production of goods $1,\ldots ,n$ , which it produces using raw materials $1,\ldots ,m$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] To produce one unit of good i , the factory needs $A_{ji}\geq 0$ units of raw material j .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Let x be the factory's production schedule (produce $x_{i}$ units of good i ), let $c\geq 0$ be the market prices (a unit of good i can sell for $c_{i}$ ), and let $b\geq 0$ be the amounts of raw material that the factory has available (it has $b_{j}$ units of raw material j ).
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The constraints are that $x\geq 0$ (it cannot produce negative goods), and that the factory can only produce as many goods as is allowed by its amounts of raw materials, i.e., $Ax\leq b$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The factory wishes to maximize its total revenue $c^{\top }x$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Now consider another factory that wishes to purchase the entire stock of raw material b from the previous factory.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] It offers a price vector of y (a unit of raw material i for $y_{i}$ ).
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] For the offer to be accepted, it should be the case that $A^{T}y\geq c$ , as otherwise the first factory could earn more cash by producing a certain product than selling off the raw material used to produce the goods.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] It also should be $y\geq 0$ , since the first factory would not sell its materials for a negative price.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The second factory wishes to minimize the amount $b^{\top }y$ that it pays for the first factory's entire stock of raw materials.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The duality theorem states that the duality gap between the two LP problems is non-negative.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In other words, an optimal solution to this dual LP is *at least* as large as an optimal solution to the primal LP, meaning that an optimal offer $b^{\top }y$ by the second factory will always be no less than the first factory's optimal revenue $c^{\top }x$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] If the first factory is given an offer to buy its entire stock of raw material, at a per-item price of y , such that $A^{\top }y\geq c,y\geq 0$ , then it should take the offer.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] It will make at least as much revenue as it could producing finished goods.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The strong duality theorem further states that the duality gap is zero.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] With strong duality, the dual solution $y^{*}$ is, economically speaking, the "equilibrium price" (see shadow price) for the raw material that a factory with production matrix A and raw material stock b would accept for raw material, given the market price for finished goods c .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] To see why, consider if the raw material prices $y\geq 0$ are such that $(A^{T}y)_{i}<c_{i}$ for some i , then the factory would purchase more raw material to produce more of good i , since the prices are "too low".
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Conversely, if the raw material prices satisfy $A^{T}y\geq c,y\geq 0$ , but does not minimize $b^{T}y$ , then the factory would make more money by selling its raw material than producing goods, since the prices are "too high".
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] At equilibrium price $y^{*}$ , the factory cannot increase its profit by purchasing or selling off raw material.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The duality theorem has a physical interpretation too.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In general, given a primal LP, the following algorithm can be used to construct its dual LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] From this algorithm, it is easy to see that the dual of the dual is the primal.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] If all constraints have the same sign, it is possible to present the above recipe in a shorter way using matrices and vectors.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The following table shows the relation between various kinds of primals and duals.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Below, suppose the primal LP is "maximize **c**T**x** subject to [constraints]" and the dual LP is "minimize **b**T**y** subject to [constraints]".
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The **weak duality theorem** says that, for each feasible solution **x** of the primal and each feasible solution **y** of the dual: **c**T**x** ≤ **b**T**y**.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In other words, the objective value in each feasible solution of the dual is an upper-bound on the objective value of the primal, and objective value in each feasible solution of the primal is a lower-bound on the objective value of the dual.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In particular, if the primal is unbounded (from above) then the dual has no feasible solution, and if the dual is unbounded (from below) then the primal has no feasible solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The strong duality theorem is harder to prove; the proofs usually use the weak duality theorem as a sub-routine.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] One proof uses the simplex algorithm and relies on the proof that, with the suitable pivot rule, it provides a correct solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The proof establishes that, once the simplex algorithm finishes with a solution to the primal LP, it is possible to read from the final tableau, a solution to the dual LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] So, by running the simplex algorithm, we obtain solutions to both the primal and the dual simultaneously.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] So **x** must be a maximal solution of the primal LP and **y** must be a minimal solution of the dual LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] If the combined LP has no feasible solution, then the primal LP has no feasible solution either.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The strong duality theorem provides a "good characterization" of the optimal value of an LP in that it allows us to easily prove that some value *t* is the optimum of some LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] It is easy to see that the maximum of the primal LP is attained when *x*1 is minimized to its lower bound (0) and *x*2 is maximized to its upper bound under the constraint (7/6).
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Similarly, the minimum of the dual LP is attained when *y*1 is minimized to its lower bound under the constraints: the first constraint gives a lower bound of 3/5 while the second constraint gives a stricter lower bound of 4/6, so the actual lower bound is 4/6 and the minimum is 7 ⋅ 4/6 = 14/3.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In accordance with the strong duality theorem, the maximum of the primal equals the minimum of the dual.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] We use this example to illustrate the proof of the weak duality theorem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Suppose that, in the primal LP, we want to get an upper bound on the objective $3x_{1}+4x_{2}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] We can use the constraint multiplied by some coefficient, say $y_{1}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Hence, the objective of the dual LP is an upper bound on the objective of the primal LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Consider a farmer who may grow wheat and barley with the set provision of some *L* land, *F* fertilizer and *P* pesticide.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] To grow one unit of wheat, one unit of land, $F_{1}$ units of fertilizer and $P_{1}$ units of pesticide must be used.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Similarly, to grow one unit of barley, one unit of land, $F_{2}$ units of fertilizer and $P_{2}$ units of pesticide must be used.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The primal problem would be the farmer deciding how much wheat ( $x_{1}$ ) and barley ( $x_{2}$ ) to grow if their sell prices are $S_{1}$ and $S_{2}$ per unit.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] For the dual problem assume that *y* unit prices for each of these means of production (inputs) are set by a planning board.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The planning board's job is to minimize the total cost of procuring the set amounts of inputs while providing the farmer with a floor on the unit price of each of his crops (outputs), *S*1 for wheat and *S*2 for barley.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The primal problem deals with physical quantities.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] With all inputs available in limited quantities, and assuming the unit prices of all outputs is known, what quantities of outputs to produce so as to maximize total revenue?
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The dual problem deals with economic values.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] With floor guarantees on all output unit prices, and assuming the available quantity of all inputs is known, what input unit pricing scheme to set so as to minimize total expenditure?
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] To each variable in the primal space corresponds an inequality to satisfy in the dual space, both indexed by output type.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] To each inequality to satisfy in the primal space corresponds a variable in the dual space, both indexed by input type.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The coefficients that bound the inequalities in the primal space are used to compute the objective in the dual space, input quantities in this example.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The coefficients used to compute the objective in the primal space bound the inequalities in the dual space, output unit prices in this example.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Both the primal and the dual problems make use of the same matrix.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In the primal space, this matrix expresses the consumption of physical quantities of inputs necessary to produce set quantities of outputs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In the dual space, it expresses the creation of the economic values associated with the outputs from set input unit prices.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Since each inequality can be replaced by an equality and a slack variable, this means each primal variable corresponds to a dual slack variable, and each dual variable corresponds to a primal slack variable.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] This relation allows us to speak about complementary slackness.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] A LP can also be unbounded or infeasible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] However, it is possible for both the dual and the primal to be infeasible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] There is a close connection between linear programming problems, eigenequations, and von Neumann's general equilibrium model.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The solution to a linear programming problem can be regarded as a generalized eigenvector.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] where $\mathbf {p} ^{T}$ and $\mathbf {z}$ are the left and right eigenvectors of the square matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , respectively, and $\rho$ is the eigenvalue.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] where the economic meanings of $\mathbf {p}$ and $\mathbf {z}$ are the equilibrium prices of various goods and the equilibrium activity levels of various economic agents, respectively.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] where the economic meaning of $\mathbf {u}$ is the utility levels of various consumers.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] This form of the structural equilibrium model and linear programming problems can often be converted to each other, that is, the solutions to these two types of problems are often consistent.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Let us illustrate the structural equilibrium model with the previously discussed tiny example.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] These are consistent with the solutions to the linear programming problems.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The max-flow min-cut theorem is a special case of the strong duality theorem: flow-maximization is the primal LP, and cut-minimization is the dual LP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] See Max-flow min-cut theorem#Linear program formulation.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Other graph-related theorems can be proved using the strong duality theorem, in particular, Konig's theorem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] The Minimax theorem for zero-sum games can be proved using the strong-duality theorem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Sometimes, one may find it more intuitive to obtain the dual program without looking at the program matrix.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] We have *m* + *n* conditions and all variables are non-negative.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] We shall define *m* + *n* dual variables: **y**j and **s***i*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Since this is a minimization problem, we would like to obtain a dual program that is a lower bound of the primal.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] In other words, we would like the sum of all right hand side of the constraints to be the maximal under the condition that for each primal variable the sum of its coefficients do not exceed its coefficient in the linear function.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] For example, **x**1 appears in *n* + 1 constraints.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] Note that we assume in our calculations steps that the program is in standard form.
[src:hungarian-assignment/dual-linear-program] However, any linear program may be transformed to standard form and it is therefore not a limiting factor.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] In applied mathematics, the maximum **generalized assignment problem** is a problem in combinatorial optimization.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] This problem is a generalization of the assignment problem in which both tasks and agents have a size.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Moreover, the size of each task might vary from one agent to the other.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] This problem in its most general form is as follows: There are a number of agents and a number of tasks.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Any agent can be assigned to perform any task, incurring some cost and profit that may vary depending on the agent-task assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Moreover, each agent has a budget and the sum of the costs of tasks assigned to it cannot exceed this budget.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] It is required to find an assignment in which all agents do not exceed their budget and total profit of the assignment is maximized.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] In the special case in which all the agents' budgets and all tasks' costs are equal to 1, this problem reduces to the assignment problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] When the costs and profits of all tasks do not vary between different agents, this problem reduces to the multiple knapsack problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] If there is a single agent, then, this problem reduces to the knapsack problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] In the following, we have *n* kinds of items, $a_{1}$ through $a_{n}$ and *m* kinds of bins $b_{1}$ through $b_{m}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Each bin $b_{i}$ is associated with a budget $t_{i}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] For a bin $b_{i}$ , each item $a_{j}$ has a profit $p_{ij}$ and a weight $w_{ij}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] A solution is an assignment from items to bins.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] A feasible solution is a solution in which for each bin $b_{i}$ the total weight of assigned items is at most $t_{i}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The solution's profit is the sum of profits for each item-bin assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The goal is to find a maximum profit feasible solution.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The generalized assignment problem is NP-hard.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] However, there are linear-programming relaxations which give a $(1-1/e)$ -approximation.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] For the problem variant in which not every item must be assigned to a bin, there is a family of algorithms for solving the GAP by using a combinatorial translation of any algorithm for the knapsack problem into an approximation algorithm for the GAP.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Using any $\alpha$ -approximation algorithm ALG for the knapsack problem, it is possible to construct a ( $\alpha +1$ )-approximation for the generalized assignment problem in a greedy manner using a residual profit concept.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The algorithm constructs a schedule in iterations, where during iteration j a tentative selection of items to bin $b_{j}$ is selected.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The selection for bin $b_{j}$ might change as items might be reselected in a later iteration for other bins.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] The residual profit of an item $x_{i}$ for bin $b_{j}$ is $p_{ij}$ if $x_{i}$ is not selected for any other bin or $p_{ij}$ – $p_{ik}$ if $x_{i}$ is selected for bin $b_{k}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Formally: We use a vector T to indicate the tentative schedule during the algorithm.
[src:hungarian-assignment/generalized-assignment-problem] Specifically, $T[i]=j$ means the item $x_{i}$ is scheduled on bin $b_{j}$ and $T[i]=-1$ means that item $x_{i}$ is not scheduled.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The **Hungarian algorithm** or **Hungarian method** is a combinatorial optimization algorithm that solves the assignment problem in polynomial time and which anticipated later primal–dual methods.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] It was developed and published in 1955 by Harold Kuhn, who gave it the name "Hungarian method" because the algorithm was largely based on the earlier works of two Hungarian mathematicians, Dénes Kőnig and Jenő Egerváry.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] However, in 2006 it was discovered that Carl Gustav Jacobi had solved the assignment problem in the 19th century, and the solution had been published posthumously in 1890 in Latin.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] James Munkres reviewed the algorithm in 1957 and observed that it is (strongly) polynomial.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Since then the algorithm has been known also as the **Kuhn–Munkres algorithm** or **Munkres assignment algorithm**.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The time complexity of the original algorithm was $O(n^{4})$ , however Edmonds and Karp, and independently Tomizawa, noticed that it can be modified to achieve an $O(n^{3})$ running time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Ford and Fulkerson extended the method to general maximum flow problems in form of the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In this simple example, there are three workers: Alice, Bob and Carol.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] One of them has to clean the bathroom, another sweep the floors and the third washes the windows, but they each demand different pay for the various tasks.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The problem is to find the lowest-cost way to assign the jobs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The problem can be represented in a matrix of the costs of the workers doing the jobs.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian method, when applied to the above table, would give the minimum cost: this is $15, achieved by having Alice clean the bathroom, Carol sweep the floors, and Bob wash the windows.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In the matrix formulation, we are given an *n*×*n* matrix, where the element in the *i*-th row and *j*-th column represents the cost of assigning the *j*-th job to the *i*-th worker.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We have to find an assignment of the jobs to the workers, such that each job is assigned to one worker and each worker is assigned one job, such that the total cost of assignment is minimum.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If the goal is to find the assignment that yields the *maximum* cost, the problem can be solved by negating the cost matrix *C*.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The algorithm can equivalently be described by formulating the problem using a bipartite graph.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We have a complete bipartite graph $G=(S,T;E)$ with n worker vertices (S) and n job vertices (T), and the edges (E) each have a cost $c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We want to find a perfect matching with a minimum total cost.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Let us call a function $y:(S\cup T)\to \mathbb {R}$ a **potential** if $y(i)+y(j)\leq c(i,j)$ for each $i\in S,j\in T$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of each perfect matching is at least the value of each potential.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This can be seen by first noticing that the total cost of the matching is the sum of costs of all edges it contains.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of each edge is at least the sum of potentials of its endpoints.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Since the matching is perfect, each vertex is an endpoint of exactly one edge.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Hence, the total cost is at least the total potential.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian method finds a perfect matching and a potential such that the matching cost equals the potential value.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This proves that both of them are optimal.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In fact, the Hungarian method finds a perfect matching of **tight edges**: an edge $ij$ is called tight for a potential y if $y(i)+y(j)=c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Let us denote the subgraph of **tight** edges by $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The cost of a perfect matching in $G_{y}$ (if there is one) equals the value of y.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] During the algorithm we maintain a potential y and an orientation of $G_{y}$ (denoted by ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ ) which has the property that the edges oriented from T to S form a matching M.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Initially, y is 0 everywhere, and all edges are oriented from S to T (so M is empty).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In each step, either we modify y so that its value increases, or modify the orientation to obtain a matching with more edges.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We maintain the invariant that all the edges of M are tight.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In a general step, let $R_{S}\subseteq S$ and $R_{T}\subseteq T$ be the vertices not covered by M (so $R_{S}$ consists of the vertices in S with no incoming edge and $R_{T}$ consists of the vertices in T with no outgoing edge).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Let Z be the set of vertices reachable in ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ from $R_{S}$ by a directed path.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This can be computed by breadth-first search.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If $R_{T}\cap Z$ is nonempty, then reverse the orientation of all edges along a directed path in ${\overrightarrow {G_{y}}}$ from $R_{S}$ to $R_{T}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Thus the size of the corresponding matching increases by 1.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Δ is well defined because at least one such edge $ij$ must exist whenever the matching is not yet of maximum possible size (see the following section); it is positive because there are no tight edges between $Z\cap S$ and $T\setminus Z$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Increase y by Δ on the vertices of $Z\cap S$ and decrease y by Δ on the vertices of $Z\cap T$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The resulting y is still a potential, and although the graph $G_{y}$ changes, it still contains M (see the next subsections).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] By the definition of Δ the set Z of vertices reachable from $R_{S}$ increases (note that the number of tight edges does not necessarily increase).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If the vertex added to $Z\cap T$ is unmatched (that is, it is also in $R_{T}$ ), then at the next iteration the graph will have an augmenting path.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We repeat these steps until M is a perfect matching, in which case it gives a minimum cost assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The running time of this version of the method is $O(n^{4})$ : M is augmented n times, and in a phase where M is unchanged, there are at most n potential changes (since Z increases every time).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The time sufficient for a potential change is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We must show that as long as the matching is not of maximum possible size, the algorithm is always able to make progress — that is, to either increase the number of matched edges, or tighten at least one edge.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If M is of maximum possible size, we are of course finished.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, by Berge's lemma, there must exist an augmenting path P with respect to M in the underlying graph G.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] However, this path may not exist in $G_{y}$ : Although every even-numbered edge in P is tight by the definition of M, odd-numbered edges may be loose and thus absent from $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] One endpoint of P is in $R_{S}$ , the other in $R_{T}$ ; w.l.o.g., suppose it begins in $R_{S}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If every edge on P is tight, then it remains an augmenting path in $G_{y}$ and we are done.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, let $uv$ be the first loose edge on P.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If $v\notin Z$ then we have found a loose-tailed path and we are done.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, v is reachable from some other path Q of tight edges from a vertex in $R_{S}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Let $P_{v}$ be the subpath of P beginning at v and continuing to the end, and let $P'$ be the path formed by traveling along Q until a vertex on $P_{v}$ is reached, and then continuing to the end of $P_{v}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Observe that $P'$ is an augmenting path in G with at least one fewer loose edge than P.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] P can be replaced with $P'$ and this reasoning process iterated (formally, using induction on the number of loose edges) until either an augmenting path in $G_{y}$ or a loose-tailed path in G is found.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] To show that every edge in M remains after adjusting y, it suffices to show that for an arbitrary edge in M, either both of its endpoints, or neither of them, are in Z.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] To this end let $vu$ be an edge in M from T to S.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] It is easy to see that if v is in Z then u must be too, since every edge in M is tight.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Now suppose, toward contradiction, that $u\in Z$ but $v\notin Z$ . u itself cannot be in $R_{S}$ because it is the endpoint of a matched edge, so there must be some directed path of tight edges from a vertex in $R_{S}$ to u.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This path must avoid v, since that is by assumption not in Z, so the vertex immediately preceding u in this path is some other vertex $v'\in T$ . $v'u$ is a tight edge from T to S and is thus in M.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] But then M contains two edges that share the vertex u, contradicting the fact that M is a matching.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Thus every edge in M has either both endpoints or neither endpoint in Z.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] To show that y remains a potential after being adjusted, it suffices to show that no edge has its total potential increased beyond its cost.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This is already established for edges in M by the preceding paragraph, so consider an arbitrary edge uv from S to T.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If $y(u)$ is increased by Δ, then either $v\in Z\cap T$ , in which case $y(v)$ is decreased by Δ, leaving the total potential of the edge unchanged, or $v\in T\setminus Z$ , in which case the definition of Δ guarantees that $y(u)+y(v)+\Delta \leq c(u,v)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Suppose there are J jobs and W workers ( $J\leq W$ ).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We describe how to compute for each prefix of jobs the minimum total cost to assign each of these jobs to distinct workers.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Specifically, we add the j th job and update the total cost in time $O(jW)$ , yielding an overall time complexity of $O\left(\sum _{j=1}^{J}jW\right)=O(J^{2}W)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Note that this is better than $O(W^{3})$ when the number of jobs is small relative to the number of workers.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We use the same notation as the previous section, though we modify their definitions as necessary.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Let $S_{j}$ denote the set of the first j jobs and T denote the set of all workers.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Note that such potentials certify the optimality of the matching.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] During the j th step, we add the j th job to $S_{j-1}$ to form $S_{j}$ and initialize $Z=\{j\}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] At all times, every vertex in Z will be reachable from the j th job in $G_{y}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] and $w_{\text{next}}$ denote any w at which the minimum is attained.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] After adjusting the potentials in the way described in the previous section, there is now a tight edge from Z to $w_{\text{next}}$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Recomputing $\Delta$ and $w_{\text{next}}$ after changing the potentials and Z also can be done in $O(W)$ time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Case 1 can occur at most $j-1$ times before case 2 occurs and the procedure terminates, yielding the overall time complexity of $O(jW)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] For convenience of implementation, the code below adds an additional worker $w_{W}$ such that $y(w_{W})$ stores the negation of the sum of all $\Delta$ computed so far.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] After the j th job is added and the matching updated, the cost of the current matching equals the sum of all $\Delta$ computed so far, or $-y(w_{W})$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This code is adapted from e-maxx :: algo.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The Hungarian algorithm can be seen to be equivalent to the successive shortest path algorithm for minimum cost flow, where the reweighting technique from Johnson's algorithm is used to find the shortest paths.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The implementation from the previous section is rewritten below in such a way as to emphasize this connection; it can be checked that the potentials h for workers $0\dots W-1$ are equal to the potentials y from the previous solution up to a constant offset.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This variant of the algorithm follows the formulation given by Flood, and later described more explicitly by Munkres, who proved it runs in ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{4})$ time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] where $c(i,j)$ is the original cost matrix and $y(i),y(j)$ are the potentials from the graph interpretation.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Changing the potentials corresponds to adding or subtracting from rows or columns of this matrix.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The algorithm starts with $a_{ij}=c(i,j)$ .
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] As such, it can be viewed as taking the original cost matrix and modifying it.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] where a, b, c and d are workers who have to perform tasks 1, 2, 3 and 4. a1, a2, a3, and a4 denote the penalties incurred when worker "a" does task 1, 2, 3, and 4 respectively.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The problem is equivalent to assigning each worker a unique task such that the total penalty is minimized.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Note that each task can only be worked on by one worker.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This also leads to at least one zero in each row.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] As such, a naive greedy algorithm can attempt to assign all workers a task with a penalty of zero.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The zeros above would be the assigned tasks.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Worst-case there are n! combinations to try, since multiple zeroes can appear in a row if multiple elements are the minimum.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] So at some point this naive algorithm should be short circuited.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Sometimes it may turn out that the matrix at this stage cannot be used for assigning, as is the case for the matrix below.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] To overcome this, we repeat the above procedure for all columns (i.e.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] **the minimum element in each column is subtracted from all the elements in that column**) and then check if an assignment with penalty 0 is possible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] In most situations this will give the result, but if it is still not possible then we need to keep going.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] For each row, try to assign an arbitrary zero.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Assigned tasks are represented by starring a zero.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Note that assignments can't be in the same row or column.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We could end with another assignment if we choose another ordering of the rows and columns.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Cover all columns containing a (starred) zero.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Find a non-covered zero and prime it (mark it with a prime symbol).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If no such zero can be found, meaning all zeroes are covered, skip to step 5.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Substep 2: Find a primed zero on the corresponding row (there should always be one).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] We add to the path the first zero of Row 1, then the second zero of Row 1, then we are done.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] All zeros are now covered with a minimal number of rows and columns.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] The aforementioned detailed description is *just one way* to draw the minimum number of lines to cover all the 0s.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If the number of starred zeros is n (or in the general case $min(n,m)$ , where n is the number of people and m is the number of jobs), the algorithm terminates.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] See the Result subsection below on how to interpret the results.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Otherwise, find the lowest uncovered value.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Subtract this from every uncovered element and add it to every element covered by two lines.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] This is equivalent to subtracting a number from all rows which are not covered and adding the same number to all columns which are covered.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] These operations do not change optimal assignments.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] If following this specific version of the algorithm, the starred zeros form the minimum assignment.
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] From Kőnig's theorem, the minimum number of lines (minimum vertex cover) will be n (the size of maximum matching).
[src:hungarian-assignment/hungarian-algorithm] Thus, when n lines are required, minimum cost assignment can be found by looking at only zeroes in the matrix.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] The problem is a generalization of the maximum cardinality matching problem because it allows edges to carry arbitrary numerical weights.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] When all edge weights are equal, a maximum-weight matching is equivalent to a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] The maximum-weight matching problem is solvable in polynomial time using, for example, the $O(EV^{2})$ blossom algorithm, or Gabow's $O(V^{3})$ algorithm.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] This contrasts with the problem of computing the (weighted) maximum independent set of vertices in a graph, which is NP-hard.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] By adjusting the given edge weights, algorithms for the maximum-weight matching problem can also be used to solve the **maximum cardinality** maximum-weight matching problem, where the objective is to find, among all matchings with maximum cardinality, one whose total weight is maximised.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Similar ideas can also be used to solve the maximum cardinality **minimum** weight matching problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] In cases where the edge-weighted graph is bipartite, such problems are also known as the assignment problem.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] The edge weights may be positive, negative, or mixed.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] A commonly occurring variant of the problem involves computing a matching that contains as many edges as possible.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] The total weight of the matching is then used as a secondary measure.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] where C is an appropriate positive constant.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] A maximum-weight matching in $G'$ then corresponds to a maximum cardinality maximum-weight matching in G .
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Again, a maximum-weight matching on $G'$ yields a maximum cardinality minimum weight matching in G .
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] In both cases, a constant C is needed to force the algorithm to favor matchings with greater cardinality regardless of the edge weights in G .
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] The maximum-weight matching problem is solvable in polynomial time.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Other algorithms are reviewed by Duan and Pettie.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Their work also proposes an approximation algorithm for general graphs that runs in linear time for any fixed error bound.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Efficient implementations are available in several software libraries, including NetworkX, LEDA, and the LEMON graph library.
[src:hungarian-assignment/maximum-weight-matching] Maximum-weight matchings (and their maximum cardinality variants) arise in a wide range of optimization settings.
